`crates/ctx-cage/src/lifecycle/run/` orchestrates one sandboxed process invocation end-to-end: building the `bwrap`/`setsid` command line, waiting for the host-side relay socket to come up, and (via `pty/`) attaching an interactive terminal when stdin is a tty. Depending on this module gets you the full "run a caged command and get its exit status" flow; callers don't touch PTY setup or relay-wait timing directly.

The relay-wait probe (`wait_for_relay_snippet`, exercised by tests.rs) and the command-construction logic (`claude_cmd`, also tested there) live at this level, not in `pty/`; `pty/` is invoked as a subordinate step once the command line is built and the relay is confirmed up. The controlling-terminal fix (`setsid --ctty --wait`) is a correctness dependency of `pty/run_on_pty`: without it, a caged interactive process spins on `tcgetpgrp`/ENOTTY, so any change to how the command is wrapped must preserve session-leader/foreground-pgrp semantics that tests.rs checks explicitly via `/proc/self/stat`.

Ordering invariant spanning this level and `pty/`: relay-wait must complete, and the `setsid --ctty` wrapping must be in place, before `run_on_pty` spawns its relay threads — a change to spawn order here can silently reintroduce either the ENOTTY spin or the "EOF before request head" relay race. The relay-wait probe deliberately avoids a real TCP connect (uses `/proc/net/tcp`) because a real connect gets forwarded through the production relay and causes spurious startup errors; this constrains how any future readiness check at this level must be implemented too.